===Etymology 1===
{{suffix|human|ize|lang=en}}

====Verb====
{{en-verb|humaniz}}

# To make [[human]], to give or cause to have the fundamental properties of a [[human]].
#* Addison
#*: Was it the business of magic to '''humanize''' our natures with compassion?
#* {{quote-book|year=1963|author={{w|Margery Allingham}}|title={{w|The China Governess}}
|chapter=5|url=http://openlibrary.org/works/OL2004261W
|passage=A waiter brought his aperitif, which was a small scotch and soda, and as he sipped it gratefully he sighed.<br> &nbsp; &nbsp;‘Civilized,’ he said to Mr. Campion. ‘'''Humanizing'''.’ […] ‘Cigars and summer days and women in big hats with swansdown face-powder, that's what it reminds me of.’}}
# To make [[sympathetic]] or [[relatable]].
#* {{quote-book|passage=I think they would try to '''humanize''' the worst villains in history out of their fear that the audience might not like the central character.|author=Robert J. Emery|year=2000|page=267|title=The directors: in their own words|volume=2}}
#* {{quote-journal|passage=The Oscar-winning film The Iron Lady '''humanised''' Thatcher.|title=Margaret Thatcher: Let's hear it for the Iron Lady, comedy's greatest straight man|newspaper=The Independent|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/margaret-thatcher-lets-hear-it-for-the-iron-lady-comedys-greatest-straight-man-8100027.html|date=01-09-2012}}
#* {{quote-book|page=40-41|passage=Like the three ceremonial functions based on the Constitutions, these informal chief of state activities emphasize the president's role as the leader of the nation, but many of them also serve to '''humanize''' the president and symbolically bridge the gap between the president and the people.|title=The Powers of the Presidency|author=CQ Press|year=2012}}
# {{lb|en|medicine}} To [[convert]] into something human or belonging to humans.
#: ''to '''humanize''' vaccine lymph''
#: '''''humanized''' monoclonal antibodies''

